259
00:11:02,620 --> 00:11:06,860
 is actually all over the Bible, and it does not waste

260
00:11:06,860 --> 00:11:10,300
 any time describing this truth beginning in Genesis.

261
00:11:10,300 --> 00:11:12,200
 You see, we see the very first evidence of it

262
00:11:12,200 --> 00:11:14,100
 in this passage specifically.

263
00:11:14,100 --> 00:11:16,600
 It says that God is slow to anger right here

264
00:11:16,600 --> 00:11:18,140
 because although this is the first story

265
00:11:18,140 --> 00:11:21,200
 in which we see God actually express emotion,

266
00:11:21,200 --> 00:11:25,360
 the emotion he expresses is not anger, it's sorrow.

267
00:11:25,360 --> 00:11:30,360
 That's the very first emotional expression we get from God.

268
00:11:30,360 --> 00:11:33,200
 It says that he was grieved in his heart,

269
00:11:33,200 --> 00:11:34,520
 which is important because it tells us

270
00:11:34,520 --> 00:11:37,400
 that God is not bloodthirsty over humanity

271
00:11:37,400 --> 00:11:38,660
 because of their sin.

272
00:11:38,660 --> 00:11:41,880
 It tells us that God is brokenhearted over humanity

273
00:11:41,880 --> 00:11:43,420
 because of their sin.

274
00:11:43,420 --> 00:11:45,780
 That's the first evidence we get to this truth

275
00:11:45,780 --> 00:11:48,380
 that God is slow to anger, not quick,

276
00:11:48,380 --> 00:11:50,380
 as many people assume him to be.

277
00:11:50,380 --> 00:11:51,220
 But it's not just that.

278
00:11:51,220 --> 00:11:52,820
 The second evidence is not in this chapter,

279
00:11:52,820 --> 00:11:55,260
 it's in the chapter previously, and it's hard to pick up.

280
00:11:55,260 --> 00:11:56,260
 It's a very subtle detail.

281
00:11:56,260 --> 00:11:57,740
 You probably would not know it

282
00:11:57,740 --> 00:11:58,740
 if someone did not tell it to you

283
00:11:58,740 --> 00:12:00,960
 because I didn't know it until someone told it to me.

284
00:12:00,960 --> 00:12:02,540
 And yet, though we don't understand it

285
00:12:02,540 --> 00:12:06,080
 because we speak English to the ancient Israelite audience

286
00:12:06,080 --> 00:12:07,940
 to whom this was originally written and read,

287
00:12:07,940 --> 00:12:09,620
 they would have picked it up like that.

288
00:12:09,620 --> 00:12:10,740
 You see, in Genesis chapter five,

289
00:12:10,740 --> 00:12:15,080
 what you find is all of Noah's ancestral heritage.

290
00:12:15,080 --> 00:12:16,540
 It's a long genealogy.

291
00:12:16,540 --> 00:12:18,540
 It's one of those things that you typically skim through,

292
00:12:18,540 --> 00:12:20,220
 if not skip all the way over.

293
00:12:20,220 --> 00:12:21,820
 And yet, what we do when we do that

294
00:12:21,820 --> 00:12:23,100
 is we put ourselves in a position

295
00:12:23,100 --> 00:12:24,460
 where we can miss something important.

296
00:12:24,460 --> 00:12:26,500
 There's several things that actually get unpacked

297
00:12:26,500 --> 00:12:29,900
 in that genealogy that are significant.

298
00:12:29,900 --> 00:12:32,100
 Not in my notes, but I think it's valuable for you to know.

299
00:12:32,100 --> 00:12:35,180
 There's a story of Noah's great-grandfather,

300
00:12:35,180 --> 00:12:36,620
 a guy by the name of Enoch.

301
00:12:36,620 --> 00:12:38,220
 And what you see is that he walked with God

302
00:12:38,220 --> 00:12:40,580
 and then God took him before he ever knew death.

303
00:12:40,580 --> 00:12:43,660
 You don't know what's fascinating about Enoch?

304
00:12:43,660 --> 00:12:47,260
 He was a third of the life of everybody else

305
00:12:47,260 --> 00:12:49,220
 that lived during his day.

306
00:12:49,220 --> 00:12:53,140
 He was the ancient equivalent of a 30-year-old

307
00:12:53,140 --> 00:12:54,500
 in our modern moment.

308
00:12:54,500 --> 00:12:55,860
 He was only 300, not 900.

309
00:12:55,860 --> 00:12:57,460
 You know, and so what we see in Enoch

310
00:12:57,460 --> 00:13:00,540
 is that it does not take long, even in your young life,

311
00:13:00,540 --> 00:13:02,700
 you can walk with God in such a way

312
00:13:02,700 --> 00:13:04,540
 that he looks at it and he says,

313
00:13:04,540 --> 00:13:05,980
 "You know what?

314
00:13:05,980 --> 00:13:08,340
 "It's getting bad out here, isn't it?

315
00:13:08,340 --> 00:13:10,020
 "Let's get out of here."

316
00:13:10,020 --> 00:13:11,420
 That's possible.

317
00:13:11,420 --> 00:13:13,100
 Crazy to think that that's true.

318
00:13:13,100 --> 00:13:16,540
 And yet what we see is just one leg down from Enoch,

319
00:13:16,540 --> 00:13:20,380
 we meet a guy by the name of Methuselah.

320
00:13:20,380 --> 00:13:21,820
 And what's interesting about Methuselah

321
00:13:21,820 --> 00:13:26,820
 is his name means when I die, judgment,

322
00:13:26,820 --> 00:13:29,940
 which is massive when we consider

323
00:13:29,940 --> 00:13:32,580
 that God is in fact slow to anger

324
00:13:32,580 --> 00:13:34,660
 because when you look at Methuselah,

325
00:13:34,660 --> 00:13:37,100
 what you see is when he did die,

326
00:13:37,100 --> 00:13:38,740
 judgment actually did come.

327
00:13:38,740 --> 00:13:40,540
 That's when the flood began.

328
00:13:40,540 --> 00:13:42,980
 So how old is our guy, Methuselah?

329
00:13:42,980 --> 00:13:46,700
 He is 969 years old.

330
00:13:46,700 --> 00:13:51,700
 He is the longest living human in history.

331
00:13:52,820 --> 00:13:55,180
 Which is meaningful because what it tells us

332
00:13:55,180 --> 00:13:57,780
 is God is looking at this guy and he's saying,

333
00:13:57,780 --> 00:14:01,900
 "I am declaring to the world through your life

334
00:14:01,900 --> 00:14:04,460
 "that when you go, everyone goes as well.

335
00:14:04,460 --> 00:14:07,900
 "And so I'm gonna stretch your life out

336
00:14:07,900 --> 00:14:09,900
 "as long as possible because I want people

337
00:14:09,900 --> 00:14:11,420
 "to repent and believe."

338
00:14:11,420 --> 00:14:12,900
 Isn't that amazing?

339
00:14:12,900 --> 00:14:15,100
 God is slow to anger.

340
00:14:15,100 --> 00:14:16,620
 We see in 2 Peter 3, 9,

341
00:14:16,620 --> 00:14:19,580
 the Lord is not slow to fulfill his promise

342
00:14:19,580 --> 00:14:20,860
 as some count slowness,

343
00:14:20,860 --> 00:14:23,700
 but he's what he's patient toward you,

344
00:14:23,700 --> 00:14:25,460
 not wishing that any should perish,

345
00:14:25,460 --> 00:14:28,180
 but that all should reach repentance.

346
00:14:28,180 --> 00:14:29,860
 That's the second evidence.

347
00:14:29,860 --> 00:14:33,620
 And then the third evidence that we get

348
00:14:33,620 --> 00:14:36,780
 for God being slow to anger actually isn't even found

349
00:14:36,780 --> 00:14:39,060
 in the book of Genesis.

350
00:14:39,060 --> 00:14:40,820
 It's fascinating.

351
00:14:40,820 --> 00:14:42,780
 50 chapters in the book of Genesis

352
00:14:42,780 --> 00:14:44,980
 and yet God's anger though alluded to

353
00:14:44,980 --> 00:14:49,140
 is never actually spoken explicitly about,

354
00:14:49,140 --> 00:14:51,700
 which is crazy when you consider the events of Genesis.

355
00:14:51,700 --> 00:14:53,060
 We've already read some of them.

356
00:14:53,060 --> 00:14:56,100
 Like Adam and Eve, they betray God,

357
00:14:56,100 --> 00:14:59,580
 take of the fruit of good and evil and they rebel.

358
00:14:59,580 --> 00:15:02,540
 And yet God is not angry with them explicitly.

359
00:15:02,540 --> 00:15:03,940
 You move from that and you go to Cain and Abel.

360
00:15:03,940 --> 00:15:05,420
 Cain murders his brother.

361
00:15:05,420 --> 00:15:08,660
 And yet we don't see God respond angrily towards Cain.

362
00:15:08,660 --> 00:15:10,700
 You go from there and you find yourself here.

363
00:15:10,700 --> 00:15:12,580
 You go from here and you go to the next story

364
00:15:12,580 --> 00:15:15,940
 and you see yourself looking at the Tower of Babel.

365
00:15:15,940 --> 00:15:18,260
 And yet God has no anger in that story either.

366
00:15:18,260 --> 00:15:21,380
 You move out of that and you go to Sodom and Gomorrah

367
00:15:21,380 --> 00:15:22,980
 and what you find is though the people

368
00:15:22,980 --> 00:15:24,620
 are doing some really crazy things,

369
00:15:24,620 --> 00:15:28,020
 God's anger doesn't appear quite clearly there either.

370
00:15:28,020 --> 00:15:29,460
 You move out of that and you go to Abraham

371
00:15:29,460 --> 00:15:32,020
 and you see that he trades his wife into Pharaoh

372
00:15:32,020 --> 00:15:34,620
 so that way he can get favor while in Egypt.

373
00:15:34,620 --> 00:15:35,900
 And yet we don't see anger there.

374
00:15:35,900 --> 00:15:37,260
 You move out of that and you keep going

375
00:15:37,260 --> 00:15:39,620
 and you find yourself looking at the life of Jacob

376
00:15:39,620 --> 00:15:43,860
 and what happens in Jacob's life is he betrays his brother

377
00:15:43,860 --> 00:15:45,220
 and robs him of his inheritance.

378
00:15:45,220 --> 00:15:49,100
 And yet there's not necessarily anger for him there either.

379
00:15:49,100 --> 00:15:53,620
 You go past that and you see that you've got Joseph.

380
00:15:53,620 --> 00:15:55,700
 Joseph is sold by his brothers into slavery

381
00:15:55,700 --> 00:15:57,700
 and yet there's no anger there either.

382
00:15:57,700 --> 00:15:58,740
 All throughout Genesis,

383
00:15:58,740 --> 00:16:01,700
 these crazy heinous acts from mankind,

384
00:16:01,700 --> 00:16:05,620
 God is not explicitly, again, implicitly,

385
00:16:05,620 --> 00:16:07,860
 you can see this, save your email,

386
00:16:07,860 --> 00:16:11,420
 but explicitly you don't see that he is angry.

387
00:16:11,420 --> 00:16:14,300
 Again and again and again, you see he's merciful.

388
00:16:14,300 --> 00:16:16,620
 And yet the first time we see his anger

389
00:16:16,620 --> 00:16:21,620
 explicitly articulated isn't until the book of Exodus.

390
00:16:21,620 --> 00:16:23,580
 And then three times it's spoken of,

391
00:16:23,580 --> 00:16:24,900
 each of which we see the evidence

392
00:16:24,900 --> 00:16:28,180
 of his patient endurance with us

393
00:16:28,180 --> 00:16:31,020
 in the midst of our frustrating behavior.

394
00:16:31,020 --> 00:16:32,060
 We see it with Moses,

395
00:16:32,060 --> 00:16:34,500
 that very first demonstration of God's anger,

396
00:16:34,500 --> 00:16:36,380
 when he comes and he calls Moses

397
00:16:36,380 --> 00:16:39,860
 to go into free Israel out of Egyptian bondage.

398
00:16:39,860 --> 00:16:42,720
 And yet Moses, he objects to the call on God's life.

399
00:16:43,900 --> 00:16:46,040
 Not once, not twice,

400
00:16:46,040 --> 00:16:47,600
 but it takes five objections

401
00:16:47,600 --> 00:16:50,020
 before God is finally like, "Enough!"

402
00:16:50,020 --> 00:16:52,860
 That's finally when he reaches his boiling point.

403
00:16:52,860 --> 00:16:55,140
 If you move from there to the second time in Exodus,

404
00:16:55,140 --> 00:16:58,640
 you see it's when Pharaoh refused to let God's people go.

405
00:16:58,640 --> 00:17:02,060
 And yet God didn't get mad after the first plague,

406
00:17:02,060 --> 00:17:04,040
 the second plague, the third plague.

407
00:17:04,040 --> 00:17:09,180
 It took 10 before God finally felt anger towards Pharaoh.

408
00:17:09,180 --> 00:17:11,500
 And then the last one is we see,

409
00:17:11,500 --> 00:17:14,340
 is that Mount Sinai.

410
00:17:14,340 --> 00:17:16,020
 Whenever God has led Israel out

411
00:17:16,020 --> 00:17:18,900
 and it is in their moment of betrothal,

412
00:17:18,900 --> 00:17:20,580
 they're making a covenant to one another.

413
00:17:20,580 --> 00:17:23,660
 And yet as God is working out the details with Moses,

414
00:17:23,660 --> 00:17:26,420
 Israel in their darkest moment

415
00:17:26,420 --> 00:17:28,420
 betrays him by worshiping a golden calf.

416
00:17:28,420 --> 00:17:35,220
 You see, it takes a lot to evoke God's anger.

417
00:17:35,220 --> 00:17:40,540
 God's wrath is rarely in a rush,

418
00:17:40,540 --> 00:17:43,700
 which is important for us because though he is,

419
00:17:43,700 --> 00:17:48,420
 though he is angry, he is slow to anger

420
00:17:48,420 --> 00:17:50,980
 as Exodus 34 tells us.

421
00:17:50,980 --> 00:17:54,420
 It tells us this, that the Lord passed before him,

422
00:17:54,420 --> 00:17:57,060
 talking about Moses, introducing himself and proclaimed,

423
00:17:57,060 --> 00:18:00,140
 "I am the Lord, the Lord, a God merciful and gracious,

424
00:18:00,140 --> 00:18:03,960
 "slow to anger, abounding in steadfast love and faithfulness."

425
00:18:03,960 --> 00:18:07,500
 So here's the crazy thing about it.

426
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:09,980
 God, so slow to anger.

427
00:18:11,060 --> 00:18:13,060
 Is so slow to anger with you and I.

428
00:18:13,060 --> 00:18:17,060
 And yet we're so quick to anger with him.

429
00:18:17,060 --> 00:18:20,460
 We are so quick to become frustrated

430
00:18:20,460 --> 00:18:24,100
 because it's taking you longer to get the job that you want

431
00:18:24,100 --> 00:18:25,660
 or to get the relationship that you want

432
00:18:25,660 --> 00:18:27,500
 or to get better when you've been bad

433
00:18:27,500 --> 00:18:29,500
 or to actually move on from that situation.

434
00:18:29,500 --> 00:18:32,780
 And because it is taking you longer than you expected,

435
00:18:32,780 --> 00:18:35,180
 you grow frustrated with him and you accuse him

436
00:18:35,180 --> 00:18:37,260
 of acting too slow.

437
00:18:37,260 --> 00:18:38,780
 Maybe it's not that, maybe you're annoyed

438
00:18:38,780 --> 00:18:40,580
 that your actual life doesn't look as good

439
00:18:40,580 --> 00:18:42,940
 as all the edited versions of other people's lives

440
00:18:42,940 --> 00:18:44,260
 on social media.

441
00:18:44,260 --> 00:18:46,100
 And so what you feel is like God is being unjust.

442
00:18:46,100 --> 00:18:47,340
 He's being unfair to you.

443
00:18:47,340 --> 00:18:49,460
 He's been good to them, but he hasn't been good to you.

444
00:18:49,460 --> 00:18:52,140
 And so you accuse him of being unjust.

445
00:18:52,140 --> 00:18:55,300
 Maybe it's not that, maybe you're irritated

446
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:57,500
 that your friend or your family member

447
00:18:57,500 --> 00:19:02,500
 or even you yourself are constantly gripped

448
00:19:02,500 --> 00:19:05,580
 by some sort of health issue.

449
00:19:05,580 --> 00:19:08,900
 And so you look at God and what you do is you accuse him

450
00:19:08,900 --> 00:19:14,060
 of being unkind, unloving, uncaring.

451
00:19:14,060 --> 00:19:16,840
 And yet here's the crazy thing.

452
00:19:16,840 --> 00:19:20,740
 Though we often perceive God as angry with us in reality,

453
00:19:20,740 --> 00:19:23,420
 we are angry with him instead.

454
00:19:23,420 --> 00:19:25,980
 He hasn't given us what we want, who we want,

455
00:19:25,980 --> 00:19:27,660
 where we want, how we wanted it.

456
00:19:27,660 --> 00:19:31,900
 And so like little entitled, spoiled children,

457
00:19:31,900 --> 00:19:36,900
 we accuse him of being indifferent to our life,

458
00:19:36,900 --> 00:19:42,180
 insensitive to our needs, which is insane.

459
00:19:42,180 --> 00:19:43,860
 Because when you think about it,

460
00:19:43,860 --> 00:19:46,140
 there isn't an ounce of God that has proven

461
00:19:46,140 --> 00:19:48,220
 to be insensitive to your need.

462
00:19:48,220 --> 00:19:50,860
 And the reason we know it is you can look at Christ.

463
00:19:50,860 --> 00:19:55,460
 You can see in Jesus the ultimate sensitivity to your need

464
00:19:55,460 --> 00:19:57,100
 that you cannot save yourself.

465
00:19:57,100 --> 00:20:00,820
 And so he would enter into a rebellious world

466
00:20:00,820 --> 00:20:03,980
 and live a faithful life for the sake of a people

467
00:20:03,980 --> 00:20:06,260
 that were unfaithful to him.

468
00:20:06,260 --> 00:20:08,780
 God does not demonstrate in any kind of way

469
00:20:08,780 --> 00:20:10,960
 an indifference to us,

470
00:20:10,960 --> 00:20:13,140
 but instead we see his intentionality

471
00:20:13,140 --> 00:20:14,900
 in that he moves close to us

472
00:20:14,900 --> 00:20:17,020
 and he actually lives a life you can't,

473
00:20:17,020 --> 00:20:19,780
 dies the death you deserve and rises forth in victory,

474
00:20:19,780 --> 00:20:21,320
 beating death by death itself.

475
00:20:21,320 --> 00:20:24,820
 We see in Jesus the personification

476
00:20:24,820 --> 00:20:29,820
 of everything we often accuse God is not consistent with.

477
00:20:31,300 --> 00:20:36,300
 You see, we have to understand God, he has slowed anger,

478
00:20:36,300 --> 00:20:42,100
 but we too often are quick to blame.

479
00:20:42,100 --> 00:20:46,140
 And so if you feel like God is punishing you,

480
00:20:46,140 --> 00:20:50,840
 it's worth considering, does he deserve your accusation?

481
00:20:50,840 --> 00:20:52,780
 That's the first thing.

482
00:20:52,780 --> 00:20:53,940
 Second thing, let's keep going.

483
00:20:53,940 --> 00:20:56,800
 Look at chapter six, verses nine and 10.

484
00:20:59,140 --> 00:21:01,860
 It says, "These are the generations of Noah.

485
00:21:01,860 --> 00:21:03,460
 "Noah was a righteous man.

486
00:21:03,460 --> 00:21:07,180
 "Blameless in his generation, Noah walked with God.

487
00:21:07,180 --> 00:21:11,260
 "And Noah had three sons, Shem, Ham, and Japheth."

488
00:21:11,260 --> 00:21:12,640
 And as you keep reading through that chapter,

489
00:21:12,640 --> 00:21:16,020
 it gives you all the details on the ark's construction.

490
00:21:16,020 --> 00:21:18,440
 Verse 22 tells us this, "Noah did this.

491
00:21:18,440 --> 00:21:21,140
 "He did everything that God commanded him."

492
00:21:21,140 --> 00:21:22,780
 And then you go to chapter seven,

493
00:21:22,780 --> 00:21:24,440
 and it says this starting in verse one.

494
00:21:24,440 --> 00:21:26,460
 "Then the Lord said to Noah, 'Go into the ark,

495
00:21:26,460 --> 00:21:27,420
 "'you and all your household,

496
00:21:27,420 --> 00:21:29,540
 "'for I have seen that you are righteous before me

497
00:21:29,540 --> 00:21:30,600
 "'in this generation.

498
00:21:30,600 --> 00:21:33,540
 "Take with you seven pairs of all clean animals,

499
00:21:33,540 --> 00:21:34,380
 "the male and his mate,

500
00:21:34,380 --> 00:21:36,100
 "and the pair of the animals that are not clean,

501
00:21:36,100 --> 00:21:37,040
 "the male and his mate,

502
00:21:37,040 --> 00:21:39,220
 "and seven pairs of the birds of the heaven also,

503
00:21:39,220 --> 00:21:41,280
 "male and female, to keep their offspring alive

504
00:21:41,280 --> 00:21:42,440
 "on the face of all the earth.

505
00:21:42,440 --> 00:21:46,000
 "For in seven days, I will send rain on the earth,

506
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:47,460
 "40 days and 40 nights.

507
00:21:47,460 --> 00:21:48,940
 "And every living thing that I've made,

508
00:21:48,940 --> 00:21:51,060
 "I will blot out from the face of the ground.'

509
00:21:51,060 --> 00:21:53,660
 "And Noah did all that the Lord had commanded him."

510
00:21:55,220 --> 00:21:58,080
 I can't help but read this and put myself in Noah's shoes,

511
00:21:58,080 --> 00:21:59,720
 which is worth doing whenever you find yourself

512
00:21:59,720 --> 00:22:01,380
 kind of reading and working your way

513
00:22:01,380 --> 00:22:04,260
 through a narrative portion of scripture.

514
00:22:04,260 --> 00:22:05,700
 You see, it's crazy.

515
00:22:05,700 --> 00:22:08,220
 When you consider what God has actually asked Noah to do,

516
00:22:08,220 --> 00:22:10,260
 it's unfathomable.

517
00:22:10,260 --> 00:22:11,940
 Like God has looked at Noah,

518
00:22:11,940 --> 00:22:16,760
 and he has told him to build an ark on dry land,

519
